               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460223-name-850" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-850" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-850" type="surname" value="BYARS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-850" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BYARS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a baker, and live in Southampton-place, Nine Elms. I have been in the habit of employing the prisoner—on the 22nd or 23rd of Jan. I sent him out on various jobs, and the last time was with the horse and cart and five empty sacks—I gave him 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in silver to go for some saw-dust—he never returned—he ought to have returned the same evening—the horse and cart have not been found.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did this happen? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About the 22nd of Jan.—it was on a Thursday—he was apprehended about the 10th of Feb.—he had been with me about two months, backwards and forwards—he eat and drank the same as I did—I had known him about eight months—this horse was Mr. Haywood's, but he lent it to me that I could let the pri<lb></lb>soner go out—I am in partnership with my brother James—if the horse had</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602230173"></xptr>
               <p>been lost we should have been liable to pay for it, because we are in joint part<lb></lb>nership.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the prisoner acting for your brother as well as for you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, the cart was our joint property—the sacks belonged to my miller—they were in my trade, and I was answerable for them—the horse was lent to me, only on condition that my brother should sanction it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460223-name-851" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-851" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-851" type="surname" value="SPICE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-851" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED SPICE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 41.) I took the prisoner for embezzle<lb></lb>ment—I did not say anything about the cart and the sacks—on the road to the station he said he sold the horse and cart at Smithfield, but he was tipsy at the time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460223-name-852" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-852" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-852" type="surname" value="PARFETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460223-name-852" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT PARFETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I sell horses in Smithfield—the prisoner was standing at the hospital gate one afternoon, about three o'clock, with a black poney and a set of harness—I asked him who it belonged to—he said to himself, and he wanted to sell it—he said he would sell it for 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I said if I could get a customer who would give him 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., might I have what I could get over—he said I might—he said he had been selling sawdust.</p>
